children: On “HUMBLE.” Kendrick Lamar challenges his competition. It was released a week after the first promotional single,
with a music video directed by
It features religious imagery mixed with urban life, such as
—juxtaposing this with the concept of humility in the chorus.
On a religious note, the song could also be a reference to the verse
So humble yourselves before God. Resist the devil, and he will flee from you."
Kendrick told the industry to have their shit together.
produced the beat. It features a deep piano riff and a banging 808 bass line. This style of production is a departure from the sound of Kendrick’s previous jazz-influenced project,
. It seems to reference the character Deebo’s theme song from the popular comedy movie
. Kendrick is also shown riding through the neighborhood on a bicycle in the music video, similar to Deebo in
The song debuted at No. 2 on the Billboard Hot 100 on April 22, 2017, making it not only the highest charting song for Kendrick, but also one of the highest debuting hip-hop singles since
. The song later hit No. 1 on the chart on June 5, 2017, making it Lamar’s first No. 1 song and second No. 1 song overall on the charts.

class="About__Title-ut4i9m-2 kdlPmS">About</h1><div class="SongDescription__Contributors-sc-615rvk-0 hrORzd">20 Contributors</div><div class="ExpandableContent__Container-sc-1165iv-0 ikywhQ"><div class="ExpandableContent__Content-sc-1165iv-1 ewOHTu"><div class="SongDescription__Content-sc-615rvk-1 Hbxku"><div class="RichText__Container-oz284w-0 nCzQX"><p>On “HUMBLE.” Kendrick Lamar challenges his competition. It was released a week after the first promotional single, <a href="https://genius.com/Kendrick-lamar-the-heart-part-4-lyrics" rel="noopener" data-api_path="/songs/3032843">“The Heart Part 4,”</a> with a music video directed by <a href="http://davemeyers.com/" rel="noopener nofollow">Dave Meyers</a> and <a href="https://genius.com/artists/The-little-homies" rel="noopener" data-api_path="/artists/822864">The Little Homies.</a> It features religious imagery mixed with urban life, such as <a href="https://genius.com/11593050" rel="noopener" data-api_path="/referents/11593050">Kendrick in priest’s robes</a> and a moving re-enactment of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonardo_da_Vinci" rel="noopener nofollow">Leonardo Da Vinci</a>’s painting <a href="http://www.leonardodavinci.net/the-last-supper.jsp" rel="noopener nofollow"><em>The Last Supper</em></a>—juxtaposing this with the concept of humility in the chorus.</p>

<p>On a religious note, the song could also be a reference to the verse <a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=james+4%3A7&version=NLT" rel="noopener nofollow">James 4:7</a>.</p>

<blockquote><p>So humble yourselves before God. Resist the devil, and he will flee from you."</p></blockquote>

<p>—Thus linking to April 7th, the date <a href="https://genius.com/11558518" rel="noopener" data-api_path="/referents/11558518">Kendrick told the industry to have their shit together.</a></p>

<p><a href="https://genius.com/artists/Mike-will-made-it" rel="noopener" data-api_path="/artists/29978">Mike WiLL Made-It</a> produced the beat. It features a deep piano riff and a banging 808 bass line. This style of production is a departure from the sound of Kendrick’s previous jazz-influenced project, <a href="https://genius.com/albums/Kendrick-lamar/To-pimp-a-butterfly" rel="noopener" data-api_path="/albums/120991"><em>To Pimp a Butterfly</em></a>. It seems to reference the character Deebo’s theme song from the popular comedy movie <a href="http://bit.ly/2pA6OFH" rel="noopener nofollow"><i>Friday</i> (1995)</a>. Kendrick is also shown riding through the neighborhood on a bicycle in the music video, similar to Deebo in <i>Friday</i>.</p>

<p>The song debuted at No. 2 on the Billboard Hot 100 on April 22, 2017, making it not only the highest charting song for Kendrick, but also one of the highest debuting hip-hop singles since <a href="https://genius.com/genius.com/Eminem-love-the-way-you-lie-lyrics" rel="noopener">“Love the Way You Lie”</a> by <a href="https://genius.com/artists/Eminem" rel="noopener" data-api_path="/artists/45">Eminem</a>. The song later hit No. 1 on the chart on June 5, 2017, making it Lamar’s first No. 1 song and second No. 1 song overall on the charts.</p></div></div></div><button class="Button-sc-1874dbw-0
